<br />
And thankfully, this is one area where we aren't drawing down nearly so much. The USS Ronald Reagan was launched not too long ago, and there are more coming down the pipe. It is unfortunate that they are so damned expensive, because they do work very well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">No. That requires miniturizations that the North Koreans are decades from.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You could put "Little Boy" into a decent sized panel truck no problem, and that was an inefficient mess, for all the destructive power that it had. You don't need it to be the size of a watermelon for it to carve the heart out of a city.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If India so much as took a nuke out of storage, China would turn them into the glo-stick of the world.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Desperate times call for desperate measures. In the face of the strong likelihood of losing a conventional ground war, who knows what the indians might do? As for the chinese responding by turning india into a parking lot...2 major problems I see with that:
<br />
1) No point in invading a country that glows in the dark. You can't exactly live there, and all the effort in taking the place is wasted if the land isn't good for anything.
<br />
2) China would be effectively irradiating itself with massive quantities of fallout. The mountains would provide SOME cover, but the results in China would be nothing short of catastrophic.
<br />

<br />
Course, that is all extremely hypothetical...it isn't as if China isn't already suffering from an overpopulation problem. Since India is too, why go invade someone to alleviate a problem, when they are having the same problem you are? Those two countries between them have 1/3rd of the world's population.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Dude please. SARS was a joke. It killed less people in it's entire "outbreak" period than the common flu does in two days.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I wasn't attempting to say that SARS was going to wipe out civilization. It was simply to illustrate the relative lack of fundamental services.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The VAST majority of Canada's population is also condensed in a pretty small area, making the distribution of medicine, and medical treatment much easier.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Since there is no medicine that has ever existed that can treat a virus (only prevent the spread), I fail to see the individual relevance here. Is there a SARS vaccine? If so, it managed to slip heavily under the news radar. So, can't cure it, can't vaccinate against it...the key then becomes to educate about it so people can avoid the risk factors. Again, most of the SARS outbreak was in Beijing...a condensed population center, which theoretically is no different than Toronto. Yet the results turned out much different.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Bam and most major Chinese cities have nearly nothing in common.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It wasn't just the mud brick houses that failed in Bam, everything did. The Iranians are doing a whole investigation thing into why even the very newest of buildings (made out of more than glorified sand) still failed horribly.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">English policy helped shape Hong Kong, but it's still a city of millions of Chinese and regardless of who "owned" the city, the Chinese have made it what it is. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It's the policies and rules they live under that dictate the kind of success that Hong Kong enjoys, not its predominant racial makeup. Taiwan has been ruling themselves (and under circumstances far less ideal than Hong Kong), and they seem to be doing pretty well. You make it sound like I'm trying to say that the chinese people are incapable of success. That's simply not so. It's their government that holds them back. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">China is THE dominant power in Asia.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well, of course. A billion and a third people, and the largest land area (excluding as you say, Russia) in the area, they'd have to be complete buffoons to not be.<span class="gensmall"></span>


