			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The parallel I was trying to draw here was Vietnam...granted we didn't have to invade in the south, but we still lost.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Okay, thats cool but the problem with Vietnam is that we never played to win in the first place.  If our Air Force had not had such limited targeting, we would have thrashed the North.  Instead we were handcuffed to bombing only military targets.  Now, don't misunderstand and think I would approve of bombing civilians, but a lot of civilian infastructure servers a duel purpose.  A factory that makes cars can be re-tooled to make tanks or planes fairly quickly.  If we had had free reign to bomb the industrial areas and utility grids of Hanoi back into the stone age, we would have run over the north pretty quickly.
<br />

<br />
As far as riots in South Korea, I'll admit that they take place.  However it's a tiny minority of the population.  Keep in mind as well that the NK's make a passtime of slipping "sleeper" agents over the border to instigate stuff like this.  There is a certain percentage of the population that does not want us there, and they are VERY vocal.  They are, thankfully, outnumbered by the quiet majority about 100 to 1.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">You could put "Little Boy" into a decent sized panel truck no problem, and that was an inefficient mess, for all the destructive power that it had. You don't need it to be the size of a watermelon for it to carve the heart out of a city.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You're making a false comparison here.  Little Boy, for it's lack of size, was a very complex piece of machinery.  It was also an air-dropped bomb.  The fusing mechanisms for a bomb that you could just carry around in a large suitcase and remotely detonate (or even suicide-detonate) are quite a bit more complex.  You have to have a directional explosion capable of causing nuclear fusion to take place, you can't throw togather a few wads of uranium and set a match to it.  
<br />

<br />
So yes, you could put Little Boy in a big box, but unless you knew how to fuse it, it's just an inert mass.  You could jump up and down on it, you could shoot it, you could blow it up with a pipe bomb...and it wouldn't detonate (although if you blew it up with a pipe bomb it would probably irradiate a small area (few city blocks), although I'm not sure it would be at a lethal level).  Making a nuclear device is only moderatly difficult.  Wiring and fusing it to where it will create a nuclear explosion is quite difficult.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">1) No point in invading a country that glows in the dark. You can't exactly live there, and all the effort in taking the place is wasted if the land isn't good for anything. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Let me try to explain this (and Deris can probably back me up a little here).  If you have never been to an Asian country, you are arguing from a disadvantage.  They are, in many ways, totally alien to westerners.  For example, in Korea there is no concept of "standing in line."  We westerns stand in line for just about everything.  Concert tickets, DMV, amusment parks, hell we stand in lines to take a @#%$ at a baseball game.  In Korea, there is no such thing as a line (well, rarely).  They just push and shove until someone gets served or helped, and then the pushing and shoving starts again.  What I am trying to say is that we often have a very hard time understanding the way asains think.  Even those of use like myself who have spent a considerable amount of time over there are often left scratching our heads.  
<br />

<br />
The Chinese culture is very deeply rooted in honor.  Sometimes on the surface it doesn't show, and it's not as intense as it was in say, the days of the Samuri, but it's still there.  They would happily slag India even if it ment turning the country into a wasteland to avoid losing face.  If India lobbed a nuke at China, the Chinese would probably consider it disgraceful not to respond.  Unfortunatly for India that reponse would be harsh and final.
<br />

<br />
Not all wars are about ownership of land or resources.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">2) China would be effectively irradiating itself with massive quantities of fallout. The mountains would provide SOME cover, but the results in China would be nothing short of catastrophic. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes and no.  Southern China would experience some fallout, but India's populations centers are not numerous.  It wouldn't take very many nukes to kill a LOT of Indians.  Additionally, tactical nuclear weapons have come a long way.  China has not advanced as far as we have (I hope) in this realm, but they're pretty far along.  They could vaporize an armored division without doing excessive damage to nearby areas.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I wasn't attempting to say that SARS was going to wipe out civilization. It was simply to illustrate the relative lack of fundamental services. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Consider who SARS kills though.  The very young, and the very old.  Now sometimes thats not the case, but honestly those people are at risk of dying from just about anything.  I don't think it's so much a dig at the Chinese ability to control a disease as it is the fact that old people infected with respratory disease tend to die no matter how good your doctors are.  
<br />

<br />
Just like the media sensationalism of the huge flu epidemic that was supposed to happen here this year.  It's been three months...I didn't even get a flu shot and lo and behold, I LIVE!  Guess it wasn't quite as big a deal as the media wanted it to be.  The point is that the very young and elderly die, and they do it a lot more than other people.  The outbreak in China was worse that it was in Canada, and Canada has many favorable factors going for it, namely geography.  To me, saying that China has poor infastructure because a few 100 people died of SARS makes no sense.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Again, most of the SARS outbreak was in Beijing...a condensed population center, which theoretically is no different than Toronto. Yet the results turned out much different. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well, part of the problem was that the Chinese Gov't tried to cover it up, so the population didn't know about it until there were a lot of people already infected.  The communicability of SARS is pretty low anyway (or bodies would be stacking up world-wide).  Here's some more factors:
<br />

<br />
1) By the time SARS got to Canada, we already knew about it, and were able to screen for warning signs and issue travel alerts.
<br />

<br />
2) Thus, the number of carriers in Canada vs China was very small.
<br />

<br />
3) Thus, the outbreak in Canada was much smaller.
<br />

<br />
4) SARS is not fatal in the vast majority of people who contract it, so it's hard to know how many people actually got the Virus on both sides of the pond. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It wasn't just the mud brick houses that failed in Bam, everything did. The Iranians are doing a whole investigation thing into why even the very newest of buildings (made out of more than glorified sand) still failed horribly.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Okay, but regardless, if a 6.5 richter earthquake happens to epicenter near ANY major city, a lot of things are going to fall down and go boom.  There are many cities in the US that are not earthquaked proofed because there are no records of Earthquakes in that area.  If a sudden tectonic buckle caused an earthquake in Dallas those guys would be WAY screwed.  All those big glass buildings would become short glass coffins real quick.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's the policies and rules they live under that dictate the kind of success that Hong Kong enjoys, not its predominant racial makeup.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I disagree, but I have no way to prove my point so I won't argue it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A billion and a third people, and the largest land area (excluding as you say, Russia) in the area, they'd have to be complete buffoons to not be.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Having a large population does not equal power, in fact I would argue that China's population is holding them back.  Same with India.  Having a large land area also has very little to do with power.  Much of China is inhospitable mountains.  Much of Russia is frozen tundra.  
<br />

<br />
Here are the things I think that should be used to gague infastructure:
<br />

<br />
1.  Communications.  The ability to communicate in real, or near-real time, over all the population centers of the country.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
2.  A strong industrial base with enough strategic resources (both material and personnel) to run them.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
3.  A strong (not neccissarily large), well trained military, with a technological edge over your peers, and the ability to produce and maintain your own armored vehicles, planes and missiles.  China has this, and gets bonus points because not only do they make their own equipment, they're a major exporter.  
<br />

<br />
4.  An independant civilian air industry (or, more to the point, the ability of your population to get on a plane and fly somewhere else in the country).  China has this.
<br />

<br />
5.  A network of roads adaqute to allow travel in both rural and urban areas.  China has this (but I'll grant that it could be better).
<br />

<br />
6.  Electricity.  The major and lesser populcation centers have enough electricity to provide for their needs.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
7.  Water/sewage.  The ability to provide fresh water for your population centers and to remove sewage and waste from them.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
8.  Trade goods.  Having a large number of items that other countries will buy OR having the majority share of a niche item (could be a natural resource like oil, or a luxary resource like wine or precious gems) in the region.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
9.  Economy.  This is the most complicated but I would say something like this.  Having an economy in which the population has enough faith that they are not activly seeking to leave the country (or rioting).  China usually has this.  Unemployment not at a dramatic level.
<br />

<br />
10.  Stable Govornment.  A strong, central govornment that has been working for a long time.  No major rebellions, no coups, no unexpected changes of leadership.  No rapid change in system of govornment.  China has this.
<br />

<br />
Those are in no particular order, by the way.  Now, I won't argue that China does not have an infastructure equal to the US, they don't, but they would rank pretty darn high in a world wide taste test.  Just as an example I'd stack em up like this.
<br />

<br />
Grade of A+:  United States, Canada, England (UK), France, Germany (several other European nations)
<br />

<br />
Grade of A:  Japan, Australia (more European nations).
<br />

<br />
Grade of A-:  China, South Korea, Isreal, Kuwait
<br />

<br />
Grade of B+:  Russia, South Africa (borderline B), Jordan
<br />

<br />
Grade of B:  Saudi Arabia
<br />

<br />
Grade of B-:  Pakistan, maybe India
<br />

<br />
Grade of C:  Most of Eastern Europe, Lybia
<br />

<br />
Grade of D:  Pre-war Iraq, Serbia, Kosovo
<br />

<br />
Grade of F:  North Korea
<br />

<br />
Obviouslly just examples, but China ranks pretty well in my opinion.
<br />

<br />
(And Darbok, you are coming perilouslly close to what I would consider "flaming" in this section, knock it off.  I may disagree with Arriana, but at least she is capable of making an argument, and she is able to do so in a clear, well thought out manner.  This is a lot more than I can say for most people).<span class="gensmall"></span>


