</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> but unless you knew how to fuse it, it's just an inert mass.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Fusing? Huh? No, you could not LITERALLY put Little Boy onto a truck and blow it up, that wasn't what I was trying to say. The Little Boy comparison was to refute the miniturization arguement. Little Boy was still pretty big.  The point was that if a bomb could be made to fit into a truck using 1940's inexperience and technology, that making something small enough to cart around today would be a minor undertaking.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Wiring and fusing it to where it will create a nuclear explosion is quite difficult. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The difficult part is in obtaining the uranium/plutonium and purifying it. Specifically seperating out the more explosive-friendly isotopes from the isotopes that don't go "Boom" so readily. That's what all those hundreds of centrifuges we've been hearing about with the whole WMD discussion about Iraq and Libya are for. Once you have that, making it explode is easy. The technology to do that is found in any shaped-charge anti-tank missile. Making it explode with maximum efficiency...well, that does take a lot more work. But it doesn't need to be super efficient to kill a lot of people. Again, Little Boy (and Fat Man) wasted most of their material. They still worked incredibly well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If India lobbed a nuke at China, the Chinese would probably consider it disgraceful not to respond. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Oh, I'm not doubting that. It also would hardly be something exclusive to China. I don't think ANY country that got nuked wouldn't be willing to return the favor. Saving face is hardly a concept that only the chinese understand.  But invading a country with nuclear weapons, and forcing their backs up against the wall is just an invitation for disaster. The simple point was that a Chinese-Indian conflict is getting into the way-out-there hypothetical range. Well, that and...if China did invade India, and if it was kept entirely conventional, why would the US intervene, and how is it a rationalization for increasing the size of our armed forces? We've kind of gotten WAY off topic here, and that was the original point of debate.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There are many cities in the US that are not earthquaked proofed because there are no records of Earthquakes in that area. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
There actually was a fairly large quake that hit the northern midwest area some time ago (150 years? Something like that, not in more recent memory like the '06 SF quake). So even with no fault lines, it has happened and therefore could happen again. I wouldn't especially want to test the results, it would be bad...but I'd bet you we'd fare better than most places would.
<br />

<br />
You see things like the Ohio river flooding 10 feet above its banks, it wipes out some farms, some people are left homeless, lots of monetary damage...and 5 people killed. The yellow river goes an inch above its banks, and it seems as though a thousand people flop over dead. This is not something limited to China. It seems like it happens everywhere in the world except here. Natural disasters which do property damage in the US wipe out whole segments of the population almost everywhere else in the world, even "First World" countries...a couple years ago, Italy had floods that killed a few hundred people.
<br />

