</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Now, I won't argue that China does not have an infastructure equal to the US, they don't</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That's all I was really trying to say. I think that you are taking the more urbanized areas which are by necesity more advanced, and extrapolating it to the country at large to a greater degree than is true, but the basic idea is a simple one. Heck, there are a lot of areas of the US which have been "settled" for years, but lack essential services like running water and electricity.
<br />

<br />
---Edit---
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I disagree, but I have no way to prove my point so I won't argue it. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Was thinking on the subject of Hong Kong last night, and forgot to include it...to illustrate the difference, you just need to look at manufacturing. Even products made today, if you buy something made in say, Shanghai, the label will say "Made in China". If you buy something made in Hong Kong the label will say "Made in Hong Kong". So, even after China took control of the governance of HK, it still remains pretty independant of the mainland.
<br />
---End Edit---
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> if it were "not that hard" I think we'd see terrorists popping off nukes pretty steadily</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The whole terrorism thing comes from bad movie cliches like John Travolta in "Swordfish" with his (well, his character's, at least) claims of being able to buy nuclear warheads wholesale on the black market. Terrorist groups are extremely well funded, by and large. If it could be done, it would have been done. So clearly it isn't quite so easy. If they could *get* a weapon, actually using it wouldn't be that difficult. Getting the nuclear material isn't even incredibly hard. My high school chemistry teacher had some cakes of dilute uranium-bearing ore that he used to demonstrate the function of geiger counters and x-ray film and the like. Turning that into a working weapon...that's the real trick. Doing that takes things which terrorist organizations are either not good at, or would be unwise to attempt. Things like staying low profile, or concentrating your membership in a small area, or keeping up with high-maintenance machine tools, etc.<span class="gensmall"></span>


