<br />

<br />
Well, yes you're right...however I have to tack on a large "but" to my response.  At the time the war was going on Hanoi probably had more air defense artillary (AAA (anti-aicraft arty) and SAMS (surface-to-air missles) than any other spot in the world.  A smart leader, who knows his enemy doesn't really have his heart in the war, and knows that a political disaster (like shooting a shriek anti-rader missle, used to kill SAM radars through a hospital window) is going to be a very effective deterant.
<br />

<br />
Additionally, there was a lot more technological parity back then.  The N.viets were being supplied by Russia and getting first-line SAM equipment, which at the time was SA-2's, SA-3's and maybe SA-5's (although those might have come later).  Today, and SA-2's and 3's are pretty much a joke vs the countermeasure packages carried by our aircraft, and our ability to kill the radar systems that these missiles rely on for guidance is vastly more advanced.  Stealth technology was still a wet dream back in those days too, so our aircraft were much more vulnerable to being detected.
<br />

<br />
So if I'm the N.viets and I move an infantry division into a key city, I'm going to camp them next to a schoolyard, and set up a few SAM sites around them.  If my enemy (the US in this case) wants to roll the dice and risk blowing up school and the insuing media fallout, it's a gamble they were more than willing to take.  
<br />

<br />
Thus, we cant kill the SAMS, and the SAMS protect the infantry without the risk of dropping a bomb on 100 school children.  See how it all starts to roll togather nicely?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Fusing? Huh? No, you could not LITERALLY put Little Boy onto a truck and blow it up, that wasn't what I was trying to say. The Little Boy comparison was to refute the miniturization arguement. Little Boy was still pretty big. The point was that if a bomb could be made to fit into a truck using 1940's inexperience and technology, that making something small enough to cart around today would be a minor undertaking. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And the point I'm trying to make is that you're wrong.  It's still very hard to do....otherwise people would be doing it to us.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Well, that and...if China did invade India, and if it was kept entirely conventional, why would the US intervene, and how is it a rationalization for increasing the size of our armed forces? We've kind of gotten WAY off topic here, and that was the original point of debate. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The US would intervene for the same reasons we intervened in Kuwait when Iraq invaded them (although you could argue we did it to protect an ally and a source of oil).  The US would intervene for the same reasons we intervened in the Serbia/Kosovo situation (where we had nothing at all to gain).  The US would intervene for the same reasons we intervened in World War I, and World War II, to support our allies (India is considered an ally that we are on good political terms with).
<br />

<br />
As far as it's relevence to the topic of a strong armed forces, it ties in with the ability of the US military to fight two wars at once.  We could stop a Chinese invasion of India, but we couldn't stop a Chinese invasion of India AND keep a strong enough presence in Iraq.  Thus, I say the military cannot currently fulfill the ability to fight a two front war.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Natural disasters which do property damage in the US wipe out whole segments of the population almost everywhere else in the world, even "First World" countries...a couple years ago, Italy had floods that killed a few hundred people</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">. 
<br />

<br />
Ever seen what an F-5 tornado can do?  I have, first hand.  Living the first 23 years of my life in tornado ally, thats not to uncommon.  I watched an F-5 spiral down the I-35 freeway for about 20 miles.  It was so powerful it pulled chunks of the freeway out of the road-bed.  It marched down that freeway...and then it stopped.  Right over the little community of Jerald, Texas.  Thirty minutes later, there was no Jerald, Texas, and there were 60+ dead.  
<br />

<br />
More severe tornado outbreaks have killed 100's in a day.  So who's to say how many people a nautral disaster should kill?  If you're not prepared for something, it doesn't matter how good your infastructure is.  Again though, compare ANYONE to the US and it'll look like they have a weak infastrucutre.  That doesn't make it true though.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Terrorist groups are extremely well funded, by and large.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Not really.  Most are just above the level of armed rabble...and some don't even get there.  With a few very notable exceptions (Al Quida would be on, although much of their funding is history now), terrorrists are poor as hell...but they live in an area where every Tom, %$#@! and Abdhula owns an AK-47.  Don't equate having guns with good funding.  Any idiot can pick up a gun if there are an assload of guns lying around.  Its training that comes into play after that.  The US has lots of training money (compared to terrorist) thats why lots of terrorists die and not very many US troops die whenever they get into a prolonged firefight.  
<br />

<br />
Here's a quote a buddy of mine sent me recently from Afghanistan after I asked him if the AQ/Taliban are any good.
<br />

<br />
"Heeeeellllll No!  You should see these guys King (thats me).  They don't have the first concept of tactics.  Things that are first nature even to intel @#%$ like you like cover-and-move and buddy-fire.  They dont know anything about it.  Sometimes they just stand there like statues and empty clips until they over-heat their barrals or until one of us shoots them.  The only time any of our guys are getting hit is by accident.  Throw enough bullets at us and eventually someone gets hit.  
<br />

<br />
Example.  A few months ago before the snow hit we were on patrol in (removed) because a (removed) had tipped us off to AQ in the area.  So we're in 3 Humvees and it's dusk, like maybe an hour of light left.  Someone shoots an RPG at us and misses by like 100 meters and we come under small arms fire so we jump out and find cover.  We basically just lay around smoking cigarettes and @#%$ until the sun goes behind the mountains when it gets dark quick.  We pop on the night vision gogs, and see about a dozen rag heads up on this mountain side maybe 300 meters up and away from us.  Dude, the are just standing in the open, not even taking cover, and firing at us.  We killed eight of them and the rest took off.  After it was all said and done, we had fired a total of 133 rounds, or something like that.  We went up and searched the area they were in and by the next morning we had collected several RPGs that didnt work, a bunch of AKs and like 1300 shell casings.  These retards fired 1300 rounds at us, and hit nothing!  They couldn't even hit the Humvees, I think we found like a total of 13 bullet holes."
<br />

<br />
I cleaned that up a little but it's pretty much word for word.  Most terrorists have %$#@! for funding.  They are able to bully the locals into giving them stuff, and can usually scrape togather enough cash to buy guns and food, but thats about it.<span class="gensmall"></span>


