Interesting example, a tornado...a phenomena which is almost exclusively limited to the US. I did not of course mean that natural disasters NEVER kill people in the US, just the rate at which similar incidents inflict fatalities is so much lower here. If hurricane Andrew had instead been typhoon Andrew and washed up in southern India, it would have been tens of thousands (hundreds maybe?) of people killed, instead of the relatively few we had here.
