				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Heh, almost makes you wish for the days when it was "ok" to send out 300 bombers to hit one factory, and anything else that happened to get hit got a "Whoopsie". Now that we have the precision, it's expected every time, like the bombs are magical or something. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yup.  Consider in WW2 that the bombers carried nothing but dumb bombs, and they bombed from 20,000 feet using nothing but optical bomb sights...no computers, no laser targeting.  Whole chunks of cities were bombed flat in Germany.  Especially once we started getting tired of fighting and started using incindiary bombs.  Do some reading on the fire-bombing raids late in WW2 in Bremen and a few other cities.  Fires got so powerful they generated hurricane force winds and you couldn't breathe anywhere near the fire because it was consuming all the oxygen in the area.
<br />

<br />
Again, as far disasters go, natural or not, comparing any country except Canada and maybe the UK to the US will make them look bad.  Still doesn't have much to do with their overall infastrucutre.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
